column36:
HI all, at the risk of starting an uproar on my thread (please refrain - AGAIN PLEASE REFRAIN - really, stop sending me bio-weapon conspiracy stuff and telling me I will die if i don't read it) I thought i would mention the following. About one of every ten emails or messages i get have links to various sites or articles insisting that the coronavirus is a bioweapon released from a Chinese lab (intentionally or otherwise) or an American lab (intentionally or otherwise). (Even my UPS driver brought it up today.) It is not. Again, IT IS NOT. I have gone through this with the Borrelia organism as well (Plum Island) and the AIDS virus (Plum Island or God, depending on the source). It is tiresome. None of these were bio-engineered or bio-weaponized. 

I have been teaching about microbial organisms for 30 years, writing about them for 20, and going really complex tor ten. The belief that these are engineered bioweapons comes from a number of psychological roots; I understand them and why they get activated. It IS true that the powerful keep most of us out of the loop, initiate actions that affect all of us negatively from time to time (While denying responsibility), and don't really care all that much for the common people. What else is new? This has always been true. 

That plays a part in the belief that organisms are being bio-engineered but i think the stronger influence is simply our unwarranted belief that life is supposed to be safe (it isn't) and the natural world is some sort of Disney or Parkland background to our lives (it isn't). 

The truth is that microbial organisms are tightly interwoven into the ecological fabric of this planet and on this planet there is no escape from global ecology. Very few people understand what the ecological underpinnings of life are or how far astray the human species has gone from any kind of sustainable habitation of this planet. This virus, and a great many other things, are trying to explain our error to us. They will get more insistent as time goes on. 

Our technology (which comes out of the discoveries of a science that believes that dissection of the world is a legitimate approach) and our increasing population (which has come from a medical system that takes credit for the good things it does and ignores the ecological ramifications of its actions) has put unsustainable pressure on the ecological systems of the planet. 

Under that pressure the ecological systems of the planet are beginning to fail. One of the effects of that is the emergence into the human population of pandemic diseases. I and others who are knowledgeable in this area have been warning about this for thirty years. We are not immune from the ecological impacts of our species' actions. We are ecological beings on an ecological planet and our belief in American exemptionalism is unfounded. 

Microbes are some 4 billion years old, despite what most of us have been taught, and what most doctors and some scientists still believe, they are highly intelligent, are sophisticated tool users and innovators, possess language, culture, and are a great deal more sophisticated at what they are doing than we are and for sure our medical systems (which are for the most part based on inaccurate assumptions about the nature of disease and microbial pathogens and have little to no understanding of ecology). 

In the 1950s, we started a pharmaceutical war with intelligent life forms far older than our own and who have survived challenges far greater than our current ecological mess. These organisms are arising from their ecological background and entering our species simply because there are too many of us and we have disturbed the ecological balance of the planet. To them we are no different than a deer or a bird. We are in fact prey; we always have been. it is just that we have come to believe we are not and by virtue of our "intelligence" should not be. 

The great teaching of our time, despite the pain we are experiencing now (each of us will, as i already have, lose people we love), is that the way we are going about things must change. It is no longer possible to continue as we have been. Each ecological response after this one is almost certainly going to be more extreme than the last if we continue this way. 

In a sense, i guess you could say that this virus is bio-engineered BUT it has been bio-engineered by the ecological fabric of the planet, not people. The lesson here is that there are limits to our behavior that cannot be exceeded without consequences. It is a hard lesson but one we desperately need to learn. Our children deserve the effort it will take for us to learn this, as do their children, as do all our kindred life forms on this planet . . . and their children. 

In the spirit of the plants,
stephen harrod buhner

column31: Please, please, please can I ask that if we post something from someone else regarding the current pandemic, that we actually cite some sources. And not people with no credentials. For example, something from the Lancet. Not YouTube shares that end up being in violation of community rules. Not screenshots or shares of click bait. Not random rubbish from worldometers. Worldometers is not authoritative. It’s just algorithms. If you look at the meters, it’s calculated using previous statistics, (the death rate ones are using WHO data from 2016 and before). In another instance, the rate at which oil supply is diminishing is because there’s so little demand for oil, now that we’re barely driving anywhere. Worldometers will not reflect that. It’s just a running ticker based on a general formula. This is a natural remedy support network, full of highly intelligent people who can offer real support and insight into managing illnesses without the shortcuts to mainstream medical “cures”. Never have we needed it more than now, when the shortcuts are brutal untested and sometimes fatal in and of themselves. Understanding the “why” and the “how” won’t help us handle the grief, fear, panic and despair. We need to support each other the best we can. Turn to your communities to offer real, tangible support. Dear Miri, Thank you for your reply and I apologise for the delay in responding to you – as you may imagine, I have been receiving a large number of emails relating to coronavirus and am trying to answer them as quickly and thoroughly as I can. I, too, am concerned that the Coronavirus Bill grants the Government almost unprecedented powers at a time when Parliament has been essentially shut down. Whilst I welcomed the Labour amendment to require the Bill to be subject to a vote every 6 months, I think it is essential that parliamentary scrutiny of the Government is maintained in the meantime. This is why I have been writing to ministers and the speaker of the House of Commons to ask for a virtual/digital Parliament. This would be perfectly possible; the Welsh government held their plenary session using teleconferencing yesterday so assembly members were able to hear statements, ask questions and scrutinise the government. We should follow their lead. On testing, I haven’t heard any reports that people will be forced to take a test against their will. I think it would be extremely unlikely that this would happen for both rights-based and practical issues; the testing is focused on NHS staff at the moment in order to ensure that all doctors and nurses fit to work are able to do so in order to cope with the increasing numbers of patients coming in. Rest assured that I will oppose compulsory testing in the unlikely event that it is proposed by the Government. On vaccines, there haven’t been any concrete discussions of what this might look like as a viable vaccine is still at least 12-18 months in the future. However, I do not believe that every person will be required to be vaccinated, as the combination of an opt-in vaccine and the amount of people who will have already caught the virus should lead to herd immunity, rendering the need to vaccine every individual void. I hope this address your concerns! Yours sincerely, Barry

We are proud to annouce that – finally – the methodology of “our” metagenomic (also called “biological” over the last months) analysis has been published with Peer-Reviewed. It is the first publication we were awaiting, more will follow, and we know it to be long delaied compared to what we were hoping for, but the time of publishing obviously do not depend on our will, and honestly this is for us a huge achievement, no matter how long it took. The scientific journal that published our paper is F1000Research, whose reliability is factually undoubted. The informative "report" we publish here, signed by Corvelva, aims at summarizing the papers content, its validity and the reason why we consider it important. We’d like to stress this point: these data didn’t need any Peer-Review to be taken into account; these data are in the hands of EMA (European Medicines Agency), AIFA (italian regulatory body) and many regulatory agencies all over the world since months; these data have not yet been taken into account, but in the meantime the peer-reviewed publication has arrived. Something could have been done (institutionally) earlier: from now on we’ll be demanding answers, and mostly tests and verifications. As an Association, what we can frankly say is: if the criticism raised on our claims and what was found in the analysed vaccines sounded "without peer-review there is no value", now the criticism will have to be a bit more “technical” and “scientific” because of the methodology validation, now replicable. Our analyses (metagenomic for now, soon the others) are no more "Corvelva’s imaginary analyses" – as many have defined them, trying (in vain) to belittle the extent and seriousness: here they are now, with all the specifics, with clear and available data to who is willing to replicate them with integrity of purpose. We are only at the beginning, however, as all further confirmations, in-depths, verifications we have been talking about over the last few months, are already the subject of new articles to be published soon too. Enjoy the reading! P.S. it goes without saying that we, parents, members of the association, private citizens, would have preferred to give you this news at another time in history, not right in the middle of the pandemic, but please allow us a tiny bit of satisfaction in having our work finally bearing fruits, and secondly the plasure of “shutting the mouth” of evil-minded, professors-for-hire or simply bought-off people or who chose to mock rather than support an independent research aiming at confirming or refuting what we exposed, to the point of even doubting about the existence itself of the laboratories and the analyses commissioned by us: we didn’t waste any time to respond to that, facts are now doing the job. column31: Nerve damage? Possible mini stroke? Possibly something else? A very long post! Looking for some urgent help for a friend, please do help in anyway you can as she’s incredibly anxious and working herself into a right state and we are quite worried for her: Wednesday last week she had a tooth extraction done on her LEFT molar in an emergency, but as her usual holistic dentist is closed, she had to find anyone willing to see her locally. She said when the dentist injected her, it felt odd and one particular injection made her LEFT side of her neck run cold. The reason for the dental work was for 2 reasons ) she’s had a 2 year long persistent dull pain in her left tonsil that comes and goes here and there but got progressively more noticeable in the last 2 months. She suspects it was tooth related and got it pulled - still no better. There’s no lump or sign of anything suspicious in the area. Also the nerve was exposed from quite extensive decay. It was causing quite considerable pain. On and off pain. Got better then got worse. One night there was intense nerve pain near the tooth extraction so she took a single dose of Paramol as the homeopathic remedies were not working. A few hours later she woke up with an intense numb feeling in her Right side of the face, extending down to her neck and her arm and foot also experienced a milder sensation similar to her face. She checked her face in the mirror and there was no sign of her face drooping, she spoke to herself in the mirror and could talk. She assumed it was just the nerve pain from the tooth. It soon passed but her eye did feel quite displaced. She woke up in the morning with a heavy sensation in the area where the neck ran cold. Shortly after she felt her face feel slightly numb again but no tingly sensation but her eye socket felt funny. She called 111 and after 2 hours was able to speak to someone. They said as a precaution they were sending an ambulance out. Ambulance came and checked her over - all seemed ok- but they were concerned it may have been a TIA (mini stroke). They took her to a specialist hospital in London. A and E doc checked her over, said as TIA passes very quick, she can’t be sure it wasn’t that, but also wasn’t convinced it was. So as a precaution sent her to the Stroke Unit for tests the next morning. She was seen by a stroke consultant who carried out similar physical tests and said she was sure it wasn’t an actual stroke, but couldn’t rule out a TIA, however it could well have been a migraine attack or a severe case of anxiety (she has never had migraines nor anxiety before). They weren’t able to do an MRI because they are so under staffed so they did the following: CT scan to check for possible tumour (clear) Neck scan of the blood vessels and arteries (clear) ECG (clear). They told her to take blood thinners (they gave a 2 month supply) and said to wait for an MRI date to come in (it could be weeks or months). She visited a local homeopathic pharmacy to grab some aconite for her nerves , where she mentioned what happened to her. She suspected a case of a very irritated and upset nerve, so has given her a course of Arnica, Ledum and Hypercium for 3 days , plus a single dose of something else but she couldn’t recall to tell me. She’s on day 2 for that now I believe. She has woken up again this morning feel with the heavy sensation in the arm and funny in the eye. It’s not painful, but it’s there and she can’t ignore it. She’s scared To type incase she wears the arm out. I have suggested it’s just a nerve that was nipped and should take 7-8 weeks at most to start feeling better, but she says how can that be when the dental work was done on the LEFT and the problems are happening on the RIGHT? If it was a TIA I believe the symptoms are gone within hours? I know anxiety is very physical , but similar symptoms wouldn’t keep happening over the space of 48 hours would they? She has a fatty liver condition so is scared to take medicines , especially as they can’t confirm if it was a mini stroke. She says she doesn’t want to take them- I don’t think this is wise. Does anyone have any advice? She has a medical herbalist who says she might be able to help if it was caused by inflammation . She’s convinced herself she’s got permanent damage. Any ideas , experience or help you could share?

column35: Sanadroug
column36:
In the months prior to the most ferocious stock market crash in history and the eruption of the biggest public health crisis of our generation, we witnessed the biggest exodus of corporate CEOs that we have ever seen.

And as you will see below, corporate insiders also sold off billions of dollars worth of shares in their own companies just before the stock market imploded.

In life, timing can be everything, and sometimes people simply get lucky. But it does seem odd that so many among the corporate elite would be so exceedingly “lucky” all at the same time. In this article I am not claiming to know the motivations of any of these individuals, but I am pointing out certain patterns that I believe are worth investigating. One financial publication is using the phrase “the great CEO exodus” to describe the phenomenon that we have been witnessing.

It all started last year when chief executives started resigning in numbers unlike anything that we have ever seen before. The following was published by NBC News last November… Chief executives are leaving in record numbers this year, with more than 1,332 stepping aside in the period from January through the end of October, according to new data released on Wednesday.

While it’s not unusual to see CEOs fleeing in the middle of a recession, it is noteworthy to see such a rash of executive exits amid robust corporate earnings and record stock market highs. Last month, 172 chief executives left their jobs, according to executive placement firm Challenger, Gray & Christmas. It’s the highest monthly number on record, and the year-to-date total outpaces even the wave of executive exits during the financial crisis.

By the end of the year, an all-time record high 1,480 CEOs had left their posts. But to most people it seemed like the good times were still rolling at the end of 2019. Corporate profits were rising and the stock market was setting record high after record high. Yes, there were lots of signs that the global economy was really slowing down, but most experts were not forecasting an imminent recession.

So why did so many chief executives suddenly decide that it was time to move on?

The following are just a few of the big name CEOs that chose to step down in 2019…

Dennis Muilenburg — Boeing

United Airlines — Oscar Munoz

Alphabet — Larry Page

Gap — Art Peck

McDonald’s — Steve Easterbrook

Wells Fargo — Tim Sloan

Under Armour — Kevin Plank

PG&E — Geisha Williams

Kraft Heinz — Bernardo Hees

HP — Dion Weisler

Bed, Bath & Beyond — Steven Temares

Warner Bros. — Kevin Tsujihara

Best Buy — Hubert Joly

New York Post — Jesse Angelo

Colgate-Palmolive — Ian Cook

MetLife — Steven Kandarian

eBay — Devin Wenig

Nike — Mark Parker

Of course the mass exodus of chief executives did not end there.

In fact, a whopping 219 CEOs stepped down during the month of January 2020 alone. By then, it was starting to become clear that the coronavirus that was ripping through China could potentially become a major global pandemic, and I certainly can understand why many among the corporate elite would choose to abandon ship at that moment.

Some of these CEOs have made absolutely absurd salaries for many years, and it is much easier to take the money and run than it is to stick around and steer a major corporation through the most difficult global crisis that any of us have ever experienced.

The following are just a few of the well known CEOs that have resigned so far in 2020…

Bob Iger, CEO of Disney

Ginni Rometty, CEO of IBM

Harley-Davidson CEO Matt Levatich

T-Mobile’s CEO John Legere

LinkedIn CEO Jeff Weiner

Mastercard CEO Ajay Banga

Keith Block, co-CEO of Salesforce

Tidjane Thiam, CEO of Credit Suisse

Hulu CEO Randy Freer

It is important for me to say that I do not have any special insight into the personal motivations of any of these individuals, and every situation is different. But I do think that it is quite strange that we have seen such an unprecedented corporate exodus at such a critical moment in our history.

Meanwhile, top corporate executives were dumping billions of dollars worth of shares in their own companies just before the market completely cratered. The following comes from the Wall Street Journal…

“Top executives at U.S.-traded companies sold a total of roughly $9.2 billion in shares of their own companies between the start of February and the end of last week, a Wall Street Journal analysis shows. The selling saved the executives—including many in the financial industry—potential losses totaling $1.9 billion, according to the analysis, as the S&P 500 stock index plunged about 30% from its peak on Feb. 19 through the close of trading March 20.”

In the stock market, you only make money if you get out in time, and many among the corporate elite seem to have impeccable timing. Perhaps they just got really lucky. Or perhaps they were reading my articles and (truncated)
